		\begin{abstract}
			The coexistence of heterogeneous Radio Access Technologies (RATs) in Next-Generation Networks (NGN) introduces significant challenges for Service Function Chain (SFC) orchestration across edge-cloud infrastructures. Efficient deployment of Cloud-Native Network Functions (CNFs) must satisfy resource constraints, end-to-end Service-Level Agreements (SLAs), and operator-defined objectives such as energy efficiency. However, conventional Kubernetes schedulers are resource-centric and lack topology and QoS awareness. We propose OASIS, a topology-aware orchestration framework for SLA-compliant SFC placement in Multi-RAT environments. OASIS models the infrastructure as a graph and employs a Graph Attention Network (GAT) to encode resource and link heterogeneity. A Deep Reinforcement Learning (DRL) agent leverages these embeddings to derive adaptive CNF placement policies that optimize SLA compliance, resource utilization, and energy consumption using topology-aware inputs derived through Segment Routing-based telemetry. Placement decisions are translated into Kubernetes scheduling primitives and integrated with QoS-aware path realization using Segment Routing. Simulation results demonstrate that OASIS reduces SLA violations by up to 90\% across evaluated traffic classes, while improving resource utilization by approximately 19\% and reducing energy consumption by 13\% compared to baseline scheduling strategies. These results highlight the effectiveness of topology-aware learning for scalable and efficient SFC orchestration in heterogeneous Multi-RAT deployments.
		\end{abstract}
		
