		\section{Introduction}\label{intro}
		
		The evolution of wireless networks has led to the coexistence of multiple Radio Access Technologies (Multi-RAT), including legacy 4G, 5G Non-Standalone, 5G Standalone, and Wi-Fi systems. These heterogeneous RATs must be jointly orchestrated over shared edge-cloud infrastructures to support diverse service categories such as eMBB, URLLC, and massive IoT. This heterogeneity introduces significant challenges due to variations in latency, reliability, and traffic dynamics across access technologies. Consequently, orchestration decisions must account not only for compute resource availability but also for network conditions. In this context, topology awareness refers to incorporating both node-level resource states and link-level characteristics such as latency and reliability into orchestration decisions.
		
		Modern telecom cores are implemented as Cloud-Native Network Functions (CNFs) deployed over Kubernetes (K8s). Service delivery is realized through Service Function Chains (SFCs) \cite{sfc}, which define an ordered sequence of network functions (e.g., AMF, SMF, UPF) that traffic must traverse to meet service requirements. Each SFC is associated with Quality of Service (QoS) requirements and Service-Level Agreements (SLAs), typically expressed in terms of metrics such as Packet Delay Budget (PDB) and Packet Error Rate (PER). Orchestration in such environments involves determining CNF placement and routing decisions that jointly satisfy resource constraints and end-to-end QoS guarantees.
		
		In large-scale 5G vRAN deployments, operators deploy thousands of virtual Distributed Units (vDUs) across geographically distributed edge sites to meet stringent latency and capacity requirements. For instance, commercial 5G rollouts such as those by Verizon \cite{verizon_vran} involve dense edge deployments where each cell site or cluster requires localized compute for real-time processing. This results in a massive number of CNF instances being dynamically instantiated and scaled across the infrastructure. However, current orchestration mechanisms, primarily driven by resource-centric schedulers, fail to account for network topology and end-to-end QoS constraints. As a result, suboptimal placements lead to increased latency, inefficient resource utilization, and SLA violations, particularly for latency-sensitive services such as URLLC.
		
		In this work, we address the problem of coordinated CNF placement and SFC chaining path realization over a heterogeneous Multi-RAT infrastructure graph, such that end-to-end SLA constraints are satisfied while minimizing overall resource utilization and energy consumption under operator-defined policies. These policies may prioritize objectives such as peak resource efficiency (resource-aware operation) or reduced power consumption (energy-aware operation), depending on deployment requirements.
		
		Formally, the infrastructure is modeled as a graph where nodes represent compute resources with finite capacities and edges represent communication links with latency and reliability characteristics. Each SFC request imposes resource demands and QoS bounds (e.g., PDB and PER). The goal is to compute placement and path configurations satisfying these constraints while optimizing system efficiency. However, for an infrastructure with $|V|$ nodes and an SFC of length $k$, the number of possible placement configurations grows exponentially with $|V|^k$, further compounded by routing path combinations between consecutive functions. This makes exact optimization intractable for dynamic Multi-RAT environments.
		
		Existing works on DRL-based SFC orchestration primarily focus on homogeneous environments or optimize limited objectives such as latency or acceptance ratio. Furthermore, conventional Kubernetes schedulers \cite{kube-scheduler} are largely resource-centric and do not explicitly account for end-to-end QoS requirements or inter-function dependencies arising from SFC chaining, as shown in Fig.~\ref{cap}. This limitation motivates the need for an orchestration framework that jointly considers topology, QoS constraints, and operator objectives in heterogeneous Multi-RAT environments.
		
		To address this gap, we propose the OASIS framework (Orchestration of Adaptive SFC with Intelligent Sensing), a topology-aware orchestration framework for Multi-RAT networks. OASIS models the infrastructure as a dynamic graph and leverages a Graph Attention Network (GAT) to learn context-aware node embeddings that capture both resource states and link characteristics. These embeddings are utilized by a Deep Reinforcement Learning (DRL) agent to derive adaptive placement policies that satisfy SLA constraints while optimizing resource and energy objectives using topology-aware inputs derived through Segment Routing (SR)-based telemetry. This intelligent sensing capability is enabled through continuous telemetry collection from both CNFs and network devices, allowing OASIS to adapt to dynamic conditions.
		
		
		Unlike conventional Kubernetes scheduling, where CNFs are placed based solely on local resource availability and paths are computed independently thereafter, OASIS performs globally coordinated placement by incorporating both node-level resource states and link-level QoS characteristics. This ensures that feasible end-to-end SLA-compliant paths exist between consecutively placed functions. As a result, OASIS avoids scenarios where locally optimal placements lead to globally infeasible SFC realizations.
		
		
		The primary contributions of this work are as follows:
		\begin{itemize}
			\item A unified formulation of SLA-constrained SFC placement with QoS-aware path realization in heterogeneous Multi-RAT infrastructure graphs, incorporating both resource and energy considerations without combinatorial enumeration.
			\item A topology-aware embedding mechanism based on Graph Attention Networks (GAT) to encode infrastructure state and link heterogeneity.
			\item A DRL-based adaptive placement policy that jointly optimizes SLA compliance, resource utilization, and energy efficiency within a Kubernetes-based orchestration framework.
		\end{itemize}
		
